                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.841/299: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Denmark</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dodge</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Copenhagen</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-10-05T17:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 5, 1926—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 6—5:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>40. Your 34, October 4, 4 p.m. Shipping Board agent, Baltic and White Sea
                    conference, and Commercial Attaché state that tonnage duties are assessed in
                    Danish ports, but that they as well as all other charges are same for Danish and
                    all foreign including American ships except at four relatively unimportant docks
                    at Copenhagen, rarely used by foreign ships, privately owned and not subject to
                    government control, at which all foreign ships must pay fifty percent additional
                    charge.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dodge</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
